\refdeft{natural isomorphism}{4.2}{kostecki2011introduction}{
\p{A natural transformation #{\sigma: \fF \to \fG} between functors #{\fF:  \C \to \D} and #{\fG : \C \to \D} is called a \newvocab{natural isomorphism} or a \newvocab{natural equivalence}, denoted #{\sigma: \fF \cong \fG}, if each \vocab{component} #{\sigma_X : \fF(X) \to \fG(X)} is an isomorphism in #{\D}, i.e. #{\fF(X) \underset{\sigma_X}{\iso} \fG(X)}. 
}

\p{We call #{\fF} and #{\fG} \newvocab{naturally isomorphic} to each other.
}

\p{We also say that #{\fF(X) \iso \fG(X)} \newvocab{naturally in} #{X} \citet{1.3.12}{leinster2016basic}.}

\p{Diagramatically, 
